07223nam a22008295i 9781478012221DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202020ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019050692  a97814780122217 a10.1515/97814780122212doi  a(DE-B1597)554223  a(OCoLC)1153337958  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aRA395.L3bP47 2020 7aHIS0240002bisacsh04a362.109822300aPeripheral Nerve :bHealth and Medicine in Cold War Latin America /ced. by Raúl Necochea López, Anne-Emanuelle Birn. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (376 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican encounters/global interactions : 3900tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFOREWORD -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION. Alternative Destinies and Solidarities for Health and Medicine in Latin America before and during the Cold War -- tPart I. Leftist Affinities and U.S. Suspicions -- t1 Under Surveillance: Public Health, the FBI, and Exile in Cold War Mexico -- t2 National Politics and Scientific Pursuits: Medical Education and the Strategic Value of Science in Postrevolutionary Bolivia -- t3 Cold War Mexico in a Time of “Wonder Drugs” -- tPart II. Health Experts/Expertise and Contested Ideologies -- t4 The Puerto Rico Family Life Study and the Cold War Politics of Fertility Surveys -- t5 Parasitology and Communism: Public Health and Politics in Samuel Barnsley Pessoa’s Brazil -- t6 Revolutionizing Cuban Psychiatry: The Freud Wars, 1955–1970 -- tPart III. Health Politics and Publics, with and without the Cold War -- t7 From Cold War Pressures to State Policy to People’s Health: Social Medicine and Socialized Medical Care in Chile -- t8 “Psychotherapy of the Oppressed”: Anti-Imperialism and Psychoanalysis in Cold War Buenos Aires -- t9 South–South Cooperation as a Cold War Tonic: Cuban Medical Diplomacy to Sandinista Nicaragua, 1979–1990 -- tEPILOGUE. A Lingering Cold (War)? Reflections for the Present and an Agenda for Further Research -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBuenos Aires psychoanalysts resisting imperialism. Brazilian parasitologists embracing communism as an antidote to rural misery. Nicaraguan revolutionaries welcoming Cuban health cooperation. Chilean public health reformers gauging domestic approaches against Soviet and Western counterparts. These and accompanying accounts—as explored in Peripheral Nerve—problematize existing understandings of how the Cold War unfolded in Latin America, generally and in health and medical realms. Bringing together scholars from across the Americas, this volume chronicles the experiences of Latin American physicians, nurses, medical scientists, and reformers who interacted with dominant US and European players and sought alternative channels of health and medical solidarity with the Soviet Union and via South-South cooperation. Throughout, Peripheral Nerve highlights how Latin American health professionals accepted, rejected, and adapted foreign involvement; manipulated the rivalry between the United States and the USSR; and forged local variants that they projected internationally. In so doing, this collection reveals the multivalent nature of Latin American health politics, offering a significant contribution to Cold War history.Contributors. Cheasty Anderson, Anne-Emanuelle Birn, Katherine E. Bliss, Gilberto Hochman, Jennifer L. Lambe, Nicole Pacino, Carlos Henrique Assunção Paiva, Jadwiga E. Pieper Mooney, Raúl Necochea López, Marco A. Ramos, Gabriela Soto Laveaga  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCold WarxSocial aspectszLatin America. 0aMedical policyzLatin AmericaxHistory. 0aPublic healthxPolitical aspects